eoclimate Memory? -- tAfterword: The Many Uses of Climate Change -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aClimate change is one of the most pressing issues of our times, yet also seemingly intractable. This book offers novel insights on this contemporary challenge, drawing together the state-of-the-art thinking in anthropology. Approaching climate change as a nexus of nature, culture, science, politics, and belief, the book reveals nuanced ways of understanding the relationships between society and climate, science and the state, certainty and uncertainty, global and local that are manifested in climate change debates. The contributors address three major areas of inquiry: how climate change issues have been framed in previous times compared to the present; how knowledge about climate change and its impacts is produced and interpreted by different groups; and how imagination plays a role in shaping conceptions of climate change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aClimatic changes. 0aHuman ecologyvCross-cultural studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBarnes, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnes, Jessica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBecker, Austin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDove, Michael R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDove, Michael R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGiannini, Alessandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHovelsrud, Grete K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHulme, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca